\subsection{High-Level Orchestration (Raspberry Pi)}
The Raspberry Pi acts as the central brain of the system. It runs a Python-based state machine that orchestrates the entire workflow. Its primary responsibilities include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Managing the OpenCV camera feed and executing the vision pipeline.
    \item Querying the ONNX model and logging the recognized card into the local inventory database.
    \item Sending serial commands (e.g., \texttt{PICK}, \texttt{MOVE\_TO\_CAMERA}, \texttt{DROP\_BIN\_1}) to the microcontroller over a USB interface.
\end{itemize}
By offloading all physical timing constraints, the \ac{SBC} is free to utilize 100\,\% of its CPU cycles for image processing while the arm is in transit.

\subsection{Low-Level Execution (Arduino)}
The Arduino microcontroller functions as the real-time execution node. It runs a continuously polling C++ loop awaiting instructions from the \ac{SBC}. When a command is received, the Arduino:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Generates microsecond-accurate step and direction pulses for the TMC2209 driver to actuate the main axis.
    \item Transmits \ac{PWM} signals to actuate the Z-axis micro servo.
    \item Toggles the digital \ac{GPIO} pin controlling the MOSFET circuit, directly managing the 24\,V solenoid valve for pneumatic pickup and release.
\end{itemize}
This strict separation of concerns ensures that the motor movements remain perfectly smooth and deterministic, unaffected by the unpredictable OS scheduling or CPU spikes occurring on the Raspberry Pi during neural network inference.
